{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17150"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17150"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.1,0.1,0.31,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9840"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17150"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9885"},{"type":"tags","id":"9887"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23047"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESeveral physiological mechanisms help maintain lymph flow throughout the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is NOT used to help maintain lymph flow in the body?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skeletal muscle contraction","Respiratory movement","Smooth muscle contractions","Gravity","Active transport by lymphatic endothelial cells"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe following mechanisms help maintain lymph flow:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E compresses lymphatic vessels, acting as an external pump\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespiratory movement\u003C/strong\u003E creates pressure changes that help propel lymph, especially in the thorax and abdomen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmooth muscle contractions\u003C/strong\u003E in lymphatic vessel walls create intrinsic pumping action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGravity\u003C/strong\u003E assists lymph flow when body parts are elevated above the level of the heart\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport by lymphatic endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism of lymph flow - these cells form the vessel walls but do not actively pump fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese mechanisms work together with one-way valves in lymphatic vessels to ensure unidirectional flow towards the heart and prevent tissue fluid accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lymph flow is aided by skeletal muscle contraction, respiratory movements, and intrinsic smooth muscle contractions in lymphatic vessels","Gravity assists lymph flow when limbs are elevated above heart level","Multiple mechanisms work together to ensure adequate lymphatic drainage and prevent tissue oedema"],"references":["Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"ite